    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-06-05T18:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-06-05T18:30:00-05:00" n="290"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d290">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">831.24/695: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Venezuela</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Flack</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Caracas</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-06-05T19:00:00-04:30"
                            >June 5, 1943—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 6—8:27 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>519. Current Export Bulletin No. 98 received today announces effective
                    immediately newsprint paper and wheat flour are under general license. Assume
                    this means important [<hi rend="italic">Import</hi>] Recommendations not
                    required for these commodities.</p>
                <p>If this abandonment of Decentralization Plan for newsprint and flour is official,
                    effort must be made for modification of Finance Ministry resolution March 15
                    applying Decentralization Plan and requiring prior permits for imports into
                    Venezuela which now constitutes an effective barrier to general license
                    shipments excepting those valued at $25 or less.</p>
                <p>On the other hand, Department’s airgram A–620, June 1, 12:30 p.m.<note n="22"
                        xml:id="d290fn1">Not printed.</note> from BEW for Eisenhardt implies that
                    Import Recommendations are still expected for wheat flour in accordance with
                    special procedure outlined in instruction No. 1901, May 1943.<note n="22"
                        xml:id="d290fn2">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Full clarification of apparent contradiction and course of action desired is most
                    urgently requested.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Flack</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
